So in the first condition, when arr[i] is not divisible by k, the code increments the count and adds the element to the set, regardless of whether the element was already in the set. So even if the element was added before, the count is incremented again. For example, if the array has two 5's, and k=2, then each 5 will be processed as not divisible by 2, so count becomes 2, and both are added to the set (but set only has one 5). But according to the code, the count is incremented for each occurrence. But this is probably incorrect according to the problem's requirements.

The Java code adds the element to the set regardless of whether it's already present. Because the code does:

set.add(arr[i]);

